<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-05-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-05-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="499" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d499">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00Detention/67</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Secretary of War</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Good</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-04">May 4, 1929</date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">WPD 3297–32</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: With reference to your
                            letter of May 1, 1929 (Me 812.00 Detention/60 [<hi rend="italic">62</hi>]), in which you request that the United States Army authorities
                            continue to hold in custody the eighteen armed Mexican rebels who
                            recently crossed the border at Sasabe, Arizona, I am pleased to advise
                            you that this will be done and that they will not be turned over to the
                            United States Immigration authorities without prior consultation with
                            your Department.</p>
                        <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">James W. Good</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>